Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: We should start back,

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: The wildlings are dead.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Do the dead frighten you?

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: Dead is dead,

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: We have no business with the dead.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Are they dead?

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: What proof have we?

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: Will saw them,

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: If he says they are dead, that's proof enough for me.

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: My mother told me that dead men sing no songs,

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: My wet nurse said the same thing, Will,

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Never believe anything you hear at a woman's tit. There are things to be learned even from the dead.

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: We have a long ride before us,

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: Eight days, maybe nine. And night is falling.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: It does that every day about this time. Are you unmanned by the dark, Gared?

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: Bet he killed them all himself, he did,

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: twisted their little heads off, our mighty warrior.

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: Mormont said as we should track them, and we did,

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: They're dead. They shan't trouble us no more. There's hard riding before us. I don't like this weather. If it snows, we could be a fortnight getting back, and snow's the best we can hope for. Ever seen an ice storm, my lord?

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Tell me again what you saw, Will. All the details. Leave nothing out.

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: The camp is two miles farther on, over that ridge, hard beside a stream,

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: I got close as I dared. There's eight of them, men and women both. No children I could see. They put up a lean-to against the rock. The snow's pretty well covered it now, but I could still make it out. No fire burning, but the firepit was still plain as day. No one moving. I watched a long time. No living man ever lay so still.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Did you see any blood?

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Well, no,

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Did you see any weapons?

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Some swords, a few bows. One man had an axe. Heavy-looking, double-bladed, a cruel piece of iron. It was on the ground beside him, right by his hand.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Did you make note of the position of the bodies?

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: A couple are sitting up against the rock. Most of them on the ground. Fallen, like.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Or sleeping,

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Fallen,

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: There's one woman up an ironwood, half-hid in the branches. A far-eyes.

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: I took care she never saw me. When I got closer, I saw that she wasn't moving neither.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: You have a chill?

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Some,

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: The wind, m'lord.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: What do you think might have killed these men, Gared?

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: It was the cold,

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: I saw men freeze last winter, and the one before, when I was half a boy. Everyone talks about snows forty foot deep, and how the ice wind comes howling out of the north, but the real enemy is the cold. It steals up on you quieter than Will, and at first you shiver and your teeth chatter and you stamp your feet and dream of mulled wine and nice hot fires. It burns, it does. Nothing burns like the cold. But only for a while. Then it gets inside you and starts to fill you up, and after a while you don't have the strength to fight it. It's easier just to sit down or go to sleep. They say you don't feel any pain toward the end. First you go weak and drowsy, and everything starts to fade, and then it's like sinking into a sea of warm milk. Peaceful, like.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Such eloquence, Gared,

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: I never suspected you had it in you.

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: I've had the cold in me too, lordling.

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: Two ears, three toes, and the little finger off my left hand. I got off light. We found my brother frozen at his watch, with a smile on his face.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: You ought dress more warmly, Gared.

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: We'll see how warm you can dress when the winter comes.

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: If Gared said it was the cold…

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Have you drawn any watches this past week, Will?

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Yes, m'lord.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: And how did you find the Wall?

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Weeping,

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: They couldn't have froze. Not if the Wall was weeping. It wasn't cold enough.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Bright lad. We've had a few light frosts this past week, and a quick flurry of snow now and then, but surely no cold fierce enough to kill eight grown men. Men clad in fur and leather, let me remind you, with shelter near at hand, and the means of making fire.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Will, lead us there. I would see these dead men for myself.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: We can make a better pace than this, surely,

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Not with this horse,

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Perhaps my lord would care to take the lead?

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Why are you stopping?

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Best go the rest of the way on foot, m'lord. It's just over that ridge.

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: There's something wrong here,

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Is there?

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: Can't you feel it?

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: Listen to the darkness.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Wind. Trees rustling. A wolf. Which sound is it that unmans you so, Gared?

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: The trees press close here,

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: That sword will tangle you up, m'lord. Better a knife.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: If I need instruction, I will ask for it,

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Gared, stay here. Guard the horses.

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: We need a fire. I'll see to it.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: How big a fool are you, old man? If there are enemies in this wood, a fire is the last thing we want.

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: There's some enemies a fire will keep away,

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: Bears and direwolves and… and other things…

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: No fire.

Speaker: Gared
Dialogue: No fire,

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Lead on,

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Gods!

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Get down!

Speaker: Will
Dialogue: Something's wrong.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Your dead men seem to have moved camp, Will.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: On your feet, Will,

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: There's no one here. I won't have you hiding under a bush.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: I am not going back to Castle Black a failure on my first ranging. We will find these men.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Up the tree. Be quick about it. Look for a fire.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Who goes there?

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Will, where are you?

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Can you see anything?

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Answer me! Why is it so cold?

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Come no farther,

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: Dance with me then.

Speaker: Waymar Royce
Dialogue: For Robert!

Speaker: The Other
Dialogue: Unknown

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: In the name of Robert of the House Baratheon, the First of his Name, King of the Andals and the Rhoynar and the First Men, Lord of the Seven Kingdoms and Protector of the Realm, by the word of Eddard of the House Stark, Lord of Winterfell and Warden of the North, I do sentence you to die.
Listener: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Hullen;Jon Snow;Desmond

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Keep the pony well in hand,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: And don't look away. Father will know if you do.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Ass,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You did well,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: The deserter died bravely,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: He had courage, at the least.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: It was not courage. This one was dead of fear. You could see it in his eyes, Stark.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: The Others take his eyes,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: He died well. Race you to the bridge?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Done,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Are you well, Bran?

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: Yes, Father,

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: Robb says the man died bravely, but Jon says he was afraid.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: What do you think?

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: Can a man still be brave if he's afraid?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: That is the only time a man can be brave,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Do you understand why I did it?

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: He was a wildling,

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: They carry off women and sell them to the Others.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Old Nan has been telling you stories again. In truth, the man was an oathbreaker, a deserter from the Night's Watch. No man is more dangerous. The deserter knows his life is forfeit if he is taken, so he will not flinch from any crime, no matter how vile. But you mistake me. The question was not why the man had to die, but why I must do it.

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: King Robert has a headsman,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: He does,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: As did the Targaryen kings before him. Yet our way is the older way. The blood of the First Men still flows in the veins of the Starks, and we hold to the belief that the man who passes the sentence should swing the sword. If you would take a man's life, you owe it to him to look into his eyes and hear his final words. And if you cannot bear to do that, then perhaps the man does not deserve to die. One day, Bran, you will be Robb's bannerman, holding a keep of your own for your brother and your king, and justice will fall to you. When that day comes, you must take no pleasure in the task, but neither must you look away. A ruler who hides behind paid executioners soon forgets what death is.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Father, Bran, come quickly, see what Robb has found!

Speaker: Jory Cassel
Dialogue: Trouble, my lord?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Beyond a doubt,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Come, let us see what mischief my sons have rooted out now.

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: Gods!
Listener: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Harwin;Hullen;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Jory Cassel
Dialogue: Robb, get away from it!

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: She can't hurt you,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: She's dead, Jory.

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: What in the seven hells is it?
Addressee: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Harwin;Hullen;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: A wolf,

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: A freak,

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: Look at the size of it.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: It's no freak,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: That's a direwolf. They grow larger than the other kind.

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: There's not been a direwolf sighted south of the Wall in two hundred years.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I see one now,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Go on,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: You can touch him.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Here you go.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: There are five of them.

Speaker: Hullen
Dialogue: Direwolves loose in the realm, after so many years,
Addressee: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Hullen
Dialogue: I like it not.
Addressee: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Jory Cassel
Dialogue: It is a sign,
Addressee: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Hullen;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: This is only a dead animal, Jory,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Do we know what killed her?
Addressee: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Hullen;Jon Snow;Desmond

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: There's something in the throat,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: There, just under the jaw.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I'm surprised she lived long enough to whelp,
Addressee: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Hullen;Jon Snow;Desmond

Speaker: Jory Cassel
Dialogue: Maybe she didn't,

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: I've heard tales… maybe the bitch was already dead when the pups came.

Speaker: Unknown (Another man)
Dialogue: Born with the dead,
Addressee: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Hullen;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Unknown (Another man)
Dialogue: Worse luck.
Addressee: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Hullen;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Hullen
Dialogue: No matter,
Listener: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Hullen
Dialogue: They be dead soon enough too.
Listener: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: The sooner the better,
Listener: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Harwin;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: Give the beast here, Bran.

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: No!

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: It's mine.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Put away your sword, Greyjoy,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: We will keep these pups.

Speaker: Harwin
Dialogue: You cannot do that, boy,
Listener: Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Hullen;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Hullen
Dialogue: It be a mercy to kill them,
Listener: Bran Stark;Jory Cassel;Theon Greyjoy;Harwin;Jon Snow;Desmond;Eddard Stark

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Hullen speaks truly, son. Better a swift death than a hard one from cold and starvation.

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: No!

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Ser Rodrik's red bitch whelped again last week,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: It was a small litter, only two live pups. She'll have milk enough.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: She'll rip them apart when they try to nurse.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Lord Stark,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: There are five pups,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Three male, two female.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: What of it, Jon?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You have five trueborn children,
About Character: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Sansa Stark;Arya Stark;Rickon Stark

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Three sons, two daughters. The direwolf is the sigil of your House. Your children were meant to have these pups, my lord.
About Character: Robb Stark;Bran Stark;Sansa Stark;Arya Stark;Rickon Stark

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You want no pup for yourself, Jon?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: The direwolf graces the banners of House Stark,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I am no Stark, Father.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: I will nurse him myself, Father,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: I will soak a towel with warm milk, and give him suck from that.

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: Me too!

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Easy to say, and harder to do. I will not have you wasting the servants' time with this. If you want these pups, you will feed them yourselves. Is that understood?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You must train them as well,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You must train them. The kennelmaster will have nothing to do with these monsters, I promise you that. And the gods help you if you neglect them, or brutalize them, or train them badly. These are not dogs to beg for treats and slink off at a kick. A direwolf will rip a man's arm off his shoulder as easily as a dog will kill a rat. Are you sure you want this?

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: Yes, Father,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Yes,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: The pups may die anyway, despite all you do.

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: They won't die,

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: We won't let them die.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Keep them, then. Jory, Desmond, gather up the other pups. It's time we were back to Winterfell.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: What is it, Jon?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Can't you hear it?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: There,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: He must have crawled away from the others,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Or been driven away,

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: An albino,

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: This one will die even faster than the others.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I think not, Greyjoy,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: This one belongs to me.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Ned,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Catelyn,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Where are the children?
About Character: Robb Stark;Sansa Stark;Arya Stark;Bran Stark;Rickon Stark

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: In the kitchen, arguing about names for the wolf pups.
About Character: Robb Stark;Sansa Stark;Arya Stark;Bran Stark;Rickon Stark

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Arya is already in love, and Sansa is charmed and gracious, but Rickon is not quite sure.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Is he afraid?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: A little,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: He is only three.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: He must learn to face his fears. He will not be three forever. And winter is coming.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Yes,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: The man died well, I'll give him that,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I was glad for Bran's sake. You would have been proud of Bran.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I am always proud of Bran,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: He was the fourth this year,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: The poor man was half-mad. Something had put a fear in him so deep that my words could not reach him.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Ben writes that the strength of the Night's Watch is down below a thousand. It's not only desertions. They are losing men on rangings as well.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Is it the wildlings?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Who else?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: And it will only grow worse. The day may come when I will have no choice but to call the banners and ride north to deal with this King-beyond-the-Wall for good and all.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Beyond the Wall?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Mance Rayder is nothing for us to fear.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: There are darker things beyond the Wall.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You listen to too many of Old Nan's stories. The Others are as dead as the children of the forest, gone eight thousand years. Maester Luwin will tell you they never lived at all. No living man has ever seen one.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Until this morning, no living man had ever seen a direwolf either,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I ought to know better than to argue with a Tully,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You did not come here to tell me crib tales. I know how little you like this place. What is it, my lady?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: There was grievous news today, my lord. I did not wish to trouble you until you had cleansed yourself.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I am so sorry, my love. Jon Arryn is dead.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Jon…

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Is this news certain?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: It was the king's seal, and the letter is in Robert's own hand. I saved it for you. He said Lord Arryn was taken quickly. Even Maester Pycelle was helpless, but he brought the milk of the poppy, so Jon did not linger long in pain.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: That is some small mercy, I suppose,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Your sister,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: And Jon's boy. What word of them?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: The message said only that they were well, and had returned to the Eyrie,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I wish they had gone to Riverrun instead. The Eyrie is high and lonely, and it was ever her husband's place, not hers. Lord Jon's memory will haunt each stone. I know my sister. She needs the comfort of family and friends around her.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Your uncle waits in the Vale, does he not? Jon named him Knight of the Gate, I'd heard.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Brynden will do what he can for her, and for the boy. That is some comfort, but still…

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Go to her,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Take the children. Fill her halls with noise and shouts and laughter. That boy of hers needs other children about him, and Lysa should not be alone in her grief.
About Character: Lysa Arryn;Robert Arryn;Robb Stark;Sansa Stark;Arya Stark;Bran Stark;Rickon Stark

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Would that I could,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: The letter had other tidings. The king is riding to Winterfell to seek you out.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Robert is coming here?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I knew that would please you,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: We should send word to your brother on the Wall.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Yes, of course,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Ben will want to be here. I shall tell Maester Luwin to send his swiftest bird.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Damnation, how many years has it been? And he gives us no more notice than this? How many in his party, did the message say?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I should think a hundred knights, at the least, with all their retainers, and half again as many freeriders. Cersei and the children travel with them.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Robert will keep an easy pace for their sakes,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: It is just as well. That will give us more time to prepare.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: The queen's brothers are also in the party,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Well, if the price for Robert's company is an infestation of Lannisters, so be it. It sounds as though Robert is bringing half his court.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Where the king goes, the realm follows,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: It will be good to see the children. The youngest was still sucking at the Lannister woman's teat the last time I saw him. He must be, what, five by now?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Prince Tommen is seven,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: The same age as Bran. Please, Ned, guard your tongue. The Lannister woman is our queen, and her pride is said to grow with every passing year.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: There must be a feast, of course, with singers, and Robert will want to hunt. I shall send Jory south with an honor guard to meet them on the kingsroad and escort them back. Gods, how are we going to feed them all? On his way already, you said? Damn the man. Damn his royal hide.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: This is beauty. Touch it. Go on. Caress the fabric.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: Is it really mine?

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: A gift from the Magister Illyrio,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: The color will bring out the violet in your eyes. And you shall have gold as well, and jewels of all sorts. Illyrio has promised. Tonight you must look like a princess.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: Why does he give us so much?

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: What does he want from us?

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Illyrio is no fool,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: The magister knows that I will not forget my friends when I come into my throne.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Illyrio will send the slaves to bathe you. Be sure you wash off the stink of the stables. Khal Drogo has a thousand horses, tonight he looks for a different sort of mount.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: You still slouch. Straighten yourself

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Let them see that you have a woman's shape now.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: You will not fail me tonight. If you do, it will go hard for you. You don't want to wake the dragon, do you?

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Do you?

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Good.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: When they write the history of my reign, sweet sister, they will say that it began tonight.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Our land,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Ours by blood right, taken from us by treachery, but ours still, ours forever. You do not steal from the dragon, oh, no. The dragon remembers.

Speaker: Willem Darry
Dialogue: Little Princess

Speaker: Willem Darry
Dialogue: My Lady,
the beggar king.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: We will have it all back someday, sweet sister,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: The jewels and the silks, Dragonstone and King's Landing, the Iron Throne and the Seven Kingdoms, all they have taken from us, we will have it back.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: Come,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Ours is the house of the dragon,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: The fire is in our blood.

Speaker: Unknown (Illyrio's servant)
Dialogue: Drogo is so rich that even his slaves wear golden collars. A hundred thousand men ride in his khalasar, and his palace in Vaes Dothrak has two hundred rooms and doors of solid silver.

Speaker: Unknown (Illyrio's servant)
Dialogue: Now you look all a princess,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Stand there,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Turn around. Yes. Good. You look…

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Regal,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: May the Lord of Light shower you with blessings on this most fortunate day, Princess Daenerys,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: She is a vision, Your Grace, a vision,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Drogo will be enraptured.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: She's too skinny,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Are you sure that Khal Drogo likes his women this young?

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: She has had her blood. She is old enough for the khal,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Look at her. That silver-gold hair, those purple eyes… she is the blood of old Valyria, no doubt, no doubt… and highborn, daughter of the old king, sister to the new, she cannot fail to entrance our Drogo.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: I suppose,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: The savages have queer tastes. Boys, horses, sheep…

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Best not suggest this to Khal Drogo,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Do you take me for a fool?

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: I take you for a king. Kings lack the caution of common men. My apologies if I have given offense.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: We won't need his whole khalasar,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Ten thousand, that would be enough, I could sweep the Seven Kingdoms with ten thousand Dothraki screamers. The realm will rise for its rightful king. Tyrell, Redwyne, Darry, Greyjoy, they have no more love for the Usurper than I do. The Dornishmen burn to avenge Elia and her children. And the smallfolk will be with us. They cry out for their king.
About Character: Robert Baratheon;Elia Martell;Aegon Targaryen (son of Rhaegar);Rhaenys Targaryen (daughter of Rhaegar)

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: They do, don't they?

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: They are your people, and they love you well,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: In holdfasts all across the realm, men lift secret toasts to your health while women sew dragon banners and hide them against the day of your return from across the water.

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Or so my agents tell me.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: I shall kill the Usurper myself,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: as he killed my brother Rhaegar. And Lannister too, the Kingslayer, for what he did to my father.
About Character: Rhaegar Targaryen;Robert Baratheon;Aerys II Targaryen;Jaime Lannister

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: That would be most fitting,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: It is not that we fear these barbarians,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: The Lord of Light would hold our city walls against a million Dothraki, or so the red priests promise… yet why take chances, when their friendship comes so cheap?

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Insolent eunuch,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Many important men will be at the feast tonight. Such men have enemies. The khal must protect his guests, yourself chief among them, Your Grace. No doubt the Usurper would pay well for your head.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Oh, yes,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: He has tried, Illyrio, I promise you that. His hired knives follow us everywhere. I am the last dragon, and he will not sleep easy while I live.

Speaker: Unknown (Eunuch)
Dialogue: Viserys of the House Targaryen, the Third of his Name,

Speaker: Unknown (Eunuch)
Dialogue: King of the Andals and the Rhoynar and the First Men, Lord of the Seven Kingdoms and Protector of the Realm. His sister, Daenerys Stormborn, Princess of Dragonstone. His honorable host, Illyrio Mopatis, Magister of the Free City of Pentos.

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Those three are Drogo's bloodriders, there,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: By the pillar is Khal Moro, with his son Rhogoro. The man with the green beard is brother to the Archon of Tyrosh, and the man behind him is Ser Jorah Mormont.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: A knight?

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: No less.

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Anointed with the seven oils by the High Septon himself.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: What is he doing here?

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: The Usurper wanted his head,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Some trifling affront. He sold some poachers to a Tyroshi slaver instead of giving them to the Night's Watch. Absurd law. A man should be able to do as he likes with his own chattel.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: I shall wish to speak with Ser Jorah before the night is done,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Over there, sweet princess,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: there is the khal himself.

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: I must go and make my submissions,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Wait here. I shall bring him to you.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Do you see his braid, sweet sister?

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: You see how long it is?

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: When Dothraki are defeated in combat, they cut off their braids in disgrace, so the world will know their shame. Khal Drogo has never lost a fight. He is Aegon the Dragonlord come again, and you will be his queen.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: I don't want to be his queen,

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: Please, please, Viserys, I don't want to, I want to go home.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Home?

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: How are we to go home, sweet sister? They took our home from us!

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: How are we to go home?

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: I don't know…

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: I do,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: We go home with an army, sweet sister. With Khal Drogo's army, that is how we go home. And if you must wed him and bed him for that, you will.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: I'd let his whole khalasar fuck you if need be, sweet sister, all forty thousand men, and their horses too if that was what it took to get my army. Be grateful it is only Drogo. In time you may even learn to like him. Now dry your eyes. Illyrio is bringing him over, and he will not see you crying.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Smile,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: And stand up straight. Let him see that you have breasts. Gods know, you have little enough as is.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Ned! Ah, but it is good to see that frozen face of yours.
Listener: Jaime Lannister;Sandor Clegane;Joffrey Baratheon;Tyrion Lannister;Cersei Lannister;Myrcella Baratheon;Tommen Baratheon;Catelyn Stark;Robb Stark;Sansa Stark;Bran Stark;Arya Stark;Rickon Stark

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: You have not changed at all.
Listener: Jaime Lannister;Sandor Clegane;Joffrey Baratheon;Tyrion Lannister;Cersei Lannister;Myrcella Baratheon;Tommen Baratheon;Catelyn Stark;Robb Stark;Sansa Stark;Bran Stark;Arya Stark;Rickon Stark

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Your Grace. Winterfell is yours.
Listener: Jaime Lannister;Sandor Clegane;Joffrey Baratheon;Tyrion Lannister;Cersei Lannister;Myrcella Baratheon;Tommen Baratheon;Catelyn Stark;Robb Stark;Sansa Stark;Bran Stark;Arya Stark;Rickon Stark

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Take me down to your crypt, Eddard. I would pay my respects.
Listener: Jaime Lannister;Sandor Clegane;Joffrey Baratheon;Tyrion Lannister;Cersei Lannister;Myrcella Baratheon;Tommen Baratheon;Catelyn Stark;Robb Stark;Sansa Stark;Bran Stark;Arya Stark;Rickon Stark

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I was starting to think we would never reach Winterfell,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: In the south, the way they talk about my Seven Kingdoms, a man forgets that your part is as big as the other six combined.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I trust you enjoyed the journey, Your Grace?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Bogs and forests and fields, and scarcely a decent inn north of the Neck. I've never seen such a vast emptiness. Where are all your people?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Likely they were too shy to come out,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Kings are a rare sight in the north.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: More likely they were hiding under the snow. Snow, Ned!

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Late summer snows are common enough,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I hope they did not trouble you. They are usually mild.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: The Others take your mild snows,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: What will this place be like in winter? I shudder to think.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: The winters are hard,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: But the Starks will endure. We always have.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: You need to come south,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: You need a taste of summer before it flees. In Highgarden there are fields of golden roses that stretch away as far as the eye can see. The fruits are so ripe they explode in your mouth—melons, peaches, fireplums, you've never tasted such sweetness. You'll see, I brought you some. Even at Storm's End, with that good wind off the bay, the days are so hot you can barely move. And you ought to see the towns, Ned! Flowers everywhere, the markets bursting with food, the summerwines so cheap and so good that you can get drunk just breathing the air. Everyone is fat and drunk and rich.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: And the girls, Ned!

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I swear, women lose all modesty in the heat. They swim naked in the river, right beneath the castle. Even in the streets, it's too damn hot for wool or fur, so they go around in these short gowns, silk if they have the silver and cotton if not, but it's all the same when they start sweating and the cloth sticks to their skin, they might as well be naked.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Your Grace,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: She is down at the end, with Father and Brandon.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Here,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: She was more beautiful than that,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Ah, damn it, Ned, did you have to bury her in a place like this?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: She deserved more than darkness…

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: She was a Stark of Winterfell,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: This is her place.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: She should be on a hill somewhere, under a fruit tree, with the sun and clouds above her and the rain to wash her clean.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I was with her when she died,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: She wanted to come home, to rest beside Brandon and Father.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I bring her flowers when I can,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Lyanna was… fond of flowers.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I vowed to kill Rhaegar for what he did to her.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You did,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Only once,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: In my dreams, I kill him every night,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: A thousand deaths will still be less than he deserves.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: We should return, Your Grace. Your wife will be waiting.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: The Others take my wife,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: And if I hear 'Your Grace' once more, I'll have your head on a spike. We are more to each other than that.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I had not forgotten,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Tell me about Jon.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I have never seen a man sicken so quickly. We gave a tourney on my son's name day. If you had seen Jon then, you would have sworn he would live forever. A fortnight later he was dead. The sickness was like a fire in his gut. It burned right through him.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I loved that old man.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: We both did.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Catelyn fears for her sister. How does Lysa bear her grief?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Not well, in truth,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I think losing Jon has driven the woman mad, Ned. She has taken the boy back to the Eyrie. Against my wishes. I had hoped to foster him with Tywin Lannister at Casterly Rock. Jon had no brothers, no other sons. Was I supposed to leave him to be raised by women?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: The wife has lost the husband,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Perhaps the mother feared to lose the son. The boy is very young.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Six, and sickly, and Lord of the Eyrie, gods have mercy,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Lord Tywin had never taken a ward before. Lysa ought to have been honored. The Lannisters are a great and noble House. She refused to even hear of it. Then she left in the dead of night, without so much as a by-your-leave. Cersei was furious.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: The boy is my namesake, did you know that? Robert Arryn. I am sworn to protect him. How can I do that if his mother steals him away?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I will take him as ward, if you wish,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Lysa should consent to that. She and Catelyn were close as girls, and she would be welcome here as well.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: A generous offer, my friend,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: but too late. Lord Tywin has already given his consent. Fostering the boy elsewhere would be a grievous affront to him.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I have more concern for my nephew's welfare than I do for Lannister pride,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: That is because you do not sleep with a Lannister.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Ah, Ned,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: you are still too serious.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I had planned to wait a few days to speak to you, but I see now there's no need for it. Come, walk with me.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: You must have wondered why I finally came north to Winterfell, after so long.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: For the joy of my company, surely,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: And there is the Wall. You need to see it, Your Grace, to walk along its battlements and talk to those who man it. The Night's Watch is a shadow of what it once was. Benjen says—

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: No doubt I will hear what your brother says soon enough,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: The Wall has stood for what, eight thousand years? It can keep a few days more. I have more pressing concerns. These are difficult times. I need good men about me. Men like Jon Arryn. He served as Lord of the Eyrie, as Warden of the East, as the Hand of the King. He will not be easy to replace.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: His son…

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: His son will succeed to the Eyrie and all its incomes,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: No more.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: The Arryns have always been Wardens of the East. The title goes with the domain.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Perhaps when he comes of age, the honor can be restored to him,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I have this year to think of, and next. A six-year-old boy is no war leader, Ned.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: In peace, the title is only an honor. Let the boy keep it. For his father's sake if not his own. Surely you owe Jon that much for his service.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Jon's service was the duty he owed his liege lord. I am not ungrateful, Ned. You of all men ought to know that. But the son is not the father. A mere boy cannot hold the east.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Enough of this. There is a more important office to discuss, and I would not argue with you.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I have need of you, Ned.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I am yours to command, Your Grace. Always.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Those years we spent in the Eyrie… gods, those were good years. I want you at my side again, Ned. I want you down in King's Landing, not up here at the end of the world where you are no damned use to anybody.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I swear to you, sitting a throne is a thousand times harder than winning one. Laws are a tedious business and counting coppers is worse. And the people… there is no end of them. I sit on that damnable iron chair and listen to them complain until my mind is numb and my ass is raw. They all want something, money or land or justice. The lies they tell… and my lords and ladies are no better. I am surrounded by flatterers and fools. It can drive a man to madness, Ned. Half of them don't dare tell me the truth, and the other half can't find it. There are nights I wish we had lost at the Trident. Ah, no, not truly, but…

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I understand,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I think you do. If so, you are the only one, my old friend.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Lord Eddard Stark, I would name you the Hand of the King.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Your Grace,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I am not worthy of the honor.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: If I wanted to honor you, I'd let you retire. I am planning to make you run the kingdom and fight the wars while I eat and drink and wench myself into an early grave.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: You know the saying, about the king and his Hand?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: What the king dreams,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: the Hand builds.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I bedded a fishmaid once who told me the lowborn have a choicer way to put it. The king eats, they say, and the Hand takes the shit.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Damn it, Ned,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: You might at least humor me with a smile.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: They say it grows so cold up here in winter that a man's laughter freezes in his throat and chokes him to death,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Perhaps that is why the Starks have so little humor.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Come south with me, and I'll teach you how to laugh again,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: You helped me win this damnable throne, now help me hold it. We were meant to rule together. If Lyanna had lived, we should have been brothers, bound by blood as well as affection. Well, it is not too late. I have a son. You have a daughter. My Joff and your Sansa shall join our houses, as Lyanna and I might once have done.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Sansa is only eleven.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Old enough for betrothal. The marriage can wait a few years.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Now stand up and say yes, curse you.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Nothing would give me greater pleasure, Your Grace,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: These honors are all so unexpected. May I have some time to consider? I need to tell my wife…

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Yes, yes, of course, tell Catelyn, sleep on it if you must.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Just don't keep me waiting too long. I am not the most patient of men.
Kingslayer

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Hungry again?

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: Is this one of the direwolves I've heard so much of?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Yes,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: His name is Ghost.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: Summerwine,

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: Nothing so sweet. How many cups have you had, Jon?

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: As I feared. Ah, well. I believe I was younger than you the first time I got truly and sincerely drunk.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: A very quiet wolf,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: He's not like the others,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: He never makes a sound. That's why I named him Ghost. That, and because he's white. The others are all dark, grey or black.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: There are still direwolves beyond the Wall. We hear them on our rangings.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: Don't you usually eat at table with your brothers?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Most times,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: But tonight Lady Stark thought it might give insult to the royal family to seat a bastard among them.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: I see.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: My brother does not seem very festive tonight.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: The queen is angry too,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Father took the king down to the crypts this afternoon. The queen didn't want him to go.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: You don't miss much, do you, Jon? We could use a man like you on the Wall.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Robb is a stronger lance than I am, but I'm the better sword, and Hullen says I sit a horse as well as anyone in the castle.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: Notable achievements.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Take me with you when you go back to the Wall,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Father will give me leave to go if you ask him, I know he will.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: The Wall is a hard place for a boy, Jon.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I am almost a man grown,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I will turn fifteen on my next name day, and Maester Luwin says bastards grow up faster than other children.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: That's true enough,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Daeren Targaryen was only fourteen when he conquered Dorne,

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: A conquest that lasted a summer,

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: Your Boy King lost ten thousand men taking the place, and another fifty trying to hold it. Someone should have told him that war isn't a game.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: Also,

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: Daeren Targaryen was only eighteen when he died. Or have you forgotten that part?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I forget nothing,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I want to serve in the Night's Watch, Uncle.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: You don't know what you're asking, Jon. The Night's Watch is a sworn brotherhood. We have no families. None of us will ever father sons. Our wife is duty. Our mistress is honor.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: A bastard can have honor too,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I am ready to swear your oath.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: You are a boy of fourteen,

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: Not a man, not yet. Until you have known a woman, you cannot understand what you would be giving up.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I don't care about that!

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: You might, if you knew what it meant,

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: If you knew what the oath would cost you, you might be less eager to pay the price, son.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I'm not your son!

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: More's the pity.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: Come back to me after you've fathered a few bastards of your own, and we'll see how you feel.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I will never father a bastard,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Never!

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I must be excused,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Boy,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Is that animal a wolf?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: A direwolf,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: His name is Ghost.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: What are you doing up there? Why aren't you at the feast?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Too hot, too noisy, and I'd drunk too much wine,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I learned long ago that it is considered rude to vomit on your brother. Might I have a closer look at your wolf?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Can you climb down, or shall I bring a ladder?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Oh, bleed that,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I believe I've frightened your wolf. My apologies.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: He's not scared,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Ghost, come here. Come on. That's it.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Shy, isn't he?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Sit, Ghost,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: That's it. Keep still.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You can touch him now. He won't move until I tell him to. I've been training him.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I see,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Nice wolf.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: If I wasn't here, he'd tear out your throat,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: In that case, you had best stay close,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I am Tyrion Lannister.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I know,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: You're Ned Stark's bastard, aren't you?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Did I offend you?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Sorry. Dwarfs don't have to be tactful. Generations of capering fools in motley have won me the right to dress badly and say any damn thing that comes into my head.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: You are the bastard, though.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Lord Eddard Stark is my father,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Yes,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I can see it. You have more of the north in you than your brothers.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Half brothers,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Let me give you some counsel, bastard,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Never forget what you are, for surely the world will not. Make it your strength. Then it can never be your weakness. Armor yourself in it, and it will never be used to hurt you.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: What do you know about being a bastard?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: All dwarfs are bastards in their father's eyes.

Speaker: Jon Snow
