Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: So he did,

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: Take my hand,

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: Before you fall.

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: What are you doing?

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: How old are you, boy?

Speaker: Bran Stark
Dialogue: Seven,

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: The things I do for love,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Chayle,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I'm off to break my fast. See that you return the books to the shelves. Be gentle with the Valyrian scrolls, the parchment is very dry. Ayrmidon's Engines of War is quite rare, and yours is the only complete copy I've ever seen.

Speaker: Sandor Clegane
Dialogue: The boy is a long time dying. I wish he would be quicker about it.

Speaker: Joffrey Baratheon
Dialogue: At least he dies quietly,

Speaker: Joffrey Baratheon
Dialogue: It's the wolf that makes the noise. I could scarce sleep last night.

Speaker: Sandor Clegane
Dialogue: I could silence the creature, if it please you,

Speaker: Joffrey Baratheon
Dialogue: Send a dog to kill a dog!

Speaker: Joffrey Baratheon
Dialogue: Winterfell is so infested with wolves, the Starks would never miss one.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I beg to differ, nephew,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: The Starks can count past six. Unlike some princes I might name.

Speaker: Sandor Clegane
Dialogue: A voice from nowhere,

Speaker: Sandor Clegane
Dialogue: Spirits of the air!

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Down here.

Speaker: Sandor Clegane
Dialogue: The little lord Tyrion,

Speaker: Sandor Clegane
Dialogue: My pardons. I did not see you standing there.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I am in no mood for your insolence today.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Joffrey, it is past time you called on Lord Eddard and his lady, to offer them your comfort.

Speaker: Joffrey Baratheon
Dialogue: What good will my comfort do them?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: None,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Yet it is expected of you. Your absence has been noted.

Speaker: Joffrey Baratheon
Dialogue: The Stark boy is nothing to me,

Speaker: Joffrey Baratheon
Dialogue: I cannot abide the wailing of women.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: One word,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: and I will hit you again.

Speaker: Joffrey Baratheon
Dialogue: I'm going to tell Mother!

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: You tell your mother,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: But first you get yourself to Lord and Lady Stark, and you fall to your knees in front of them, and you tell them how very sorry you are, and that you are at their service if there is the slightest thing you can do for them or theirs in this desperate hour, and that all your prayers go with them. Do you understand? Do you?

Speaker: Sandor Clegane
Dialogue: The prince will remember that, little lord,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I pray he does,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: If he forgets, be a good dog and remind him.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Do you know where I might find my brother?

Speaker: Sandor Clegane
Dialogue: Breaking fast with the queen.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Ah,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Is Robert still abed?

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: The king has not slept at all,

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: He is with Lord Eddard. He has taken their sorrow deeply to heart.

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: He has a large heart, our Robert,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Bread,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: and two of those little fish, and a mug of that good dark beer to wash them down. Oh, and some bacon. Burn it until it turns black.

Speaker: Tommen Baratheon
Dialogue: Do you have news of Bran, Uncle?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I stopped by the sickroom last night,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: There was no change. The maester thought that a hopeful sign.

Speaker: Tommen Baratheon
Dialogue: I don't want Brandon to die,

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: Lord Eddard had a brother named Brandon as well,

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: One of the hostages murdered by Targaryen. It seems to be an unlucky name.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Oh, not so unlucky as all that, surely,

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: What do you mean?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Why, only that Tommen may get his wish. The maester thinks the boy may yet live.

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: That is no mercy. These northern gods are cruel to let the child linger in such pain.

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: What were the maester's words?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: He thinks that if the boy were going to die, he would have done so already. It has been four days with no change.

Speaker: Myrcella Baratheon
Dialogue: Will Bran get better, Uncle?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: His back is broken, little one,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: The fall shattered his legs as well. They keep him alive with honey and water, or he would starve to death. Perhaps, if he wakes, he will be able to eat real food, but he will never walk again.

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: If he wakes,

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: Is that likely?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: The gods alone know,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: The maester only hopes.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I would swear that wolf of his is keeping the boy alive. The creature is outside his window day and night, howling. Every time they chase it away, it returns. The maester said they closed the window once, to shut out the noise, and Bran seemed to weaken. When they opened it again, his heart beat stronger.

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: There is something unnatural about those animals,

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: They are dangerous. I will not have any of them coming south with us.

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: You'll have a hard time stopping them, sister. They follow those girls everywhere.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Are you leaving soon, then?

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: Not near soon enough,

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: Are we leaving?

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: What about you? Gods, don't tell me you are staying here?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Benjen Stark is returning to the Night's Watch with his brother's bastard. I have a mind to go with them and see this Wall we have all heard so much of.

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: I hope you're not thinking of taking the black on us, sweet brother.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: What, me, celibate? The whores would go begging from Dorne to Casterly Rock. No, I just want to stand on top of the Wall and piss off the edge of the world.

Speaker: Cersei Lannister
Dialogue: The children don't need to hear this filth. Tommen, Myrcella, come.

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: Stark will never consent to leave Winterfell with his son lingering in the shadow of death.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: He will if Robert commands it,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: And Robert will command it. There is nothing Lord Eddard can do for the boy in any case.

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: He could end his torment,

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: I would, if it were my son. It would be a mercy.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I advise against putting that suggestion to Lord Eddard, sweet brother,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: He would not take it kindly.

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: Even if the boy does live, he will be a cripple. Worse than a cripple. A grotesque. Give me a good clean death.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Speaking for the grotesques,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I beg to differ. Death is so terribly final, while life is full of possibilities.

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: You are a perverse little imp, aren't you?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Oh, yes,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I hope the boy does wake. I would be most interested to hear what he might have to say.

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: Tyrion, my sweet brother,

Speaker: Jaime Lannister
Dialogue: there are times when you give me cause to wonder whose side you are on.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Why, Jaime, my sweet brother,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: you wound me. You know how much I love my family.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: What are you doing here?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I came to see Bran,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: To say good-bye.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: You've said it. Now go away.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Please,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I told you to leave,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: We don't want you here.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: He's my brother,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Shall I call the guards?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Call them,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You can't stop me from seeing him.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Bran,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I'm sorry I didn't come before. I was afraid.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Don't die, Bran. Please. We're all waiting for you to wake up. Me and Robb and the girls, everyone…

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I have to go now,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Uncle Benjen is waiting. I'm to go north to the Wall. We have to leave today, before the snows come.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I wanted him to stay here with me,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I prayed for it,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: He was my special boy. I went to the sept and prayed seven times to the seven faces of god that Ned would change his mind and leave him here with me. Sometimes prayers are answered.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: It wasn't your fault,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I need none of your absolution, bastard.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Good-bye,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Jon,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Yes?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: It should have been you,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Uncle Benjen is looking for you,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: He wanted to be gone an hour ago.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I know,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Soon.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Leaving is harder than I thought.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: For me too,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Did you see him?

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: He's not going to die,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: I know it.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You Starks are hard to kill,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: My mother…

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: She was… very kind,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Good.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: The next time I see you, you'll be all in black.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: It was always my color. How long do you think it will be?

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Soon enough,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Farewell, Snow.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: And you, Stark. Take care of Bran.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: I will.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Uncle Benjen said to send you to the stables if I saw you,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I have one more farewell to make,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Then I haven't seen you,

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: I was afraid you were gone,

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: They wouldn't let me out to say good-bye.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: What did you do now?

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: Nothing. I was all packed and everything.

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: Septa Mordane says I have to do it all over. My things weren't properly folded, she says. A proper southron lady doesn't just throw her clothes inside her chest like old rags, she says.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Is that what you did, little sister?

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: Well, they're going to get all messed up anyway,

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: Who cares how they're folded?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Septa Mordane,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I don't think she'd like Nymeria helping, either.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: It's just as well. I have something for you to take with you, and it has to be packed very carefully.

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: A present?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You could call it that. Close the door.

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: Nymeria, here. Guard.

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: A sword,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: This is no toy,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Be careful you don't cut yourself. The edges are sharp enough to shave with.

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: Girls don't shave,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Maybe they should. Have you ever seen the septa's legs?

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: It's so skinny.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: So are you,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I had Mikken make this special. The bravos use swords like this in Pentos and Myr and the other Free Cities. It won't hack a man's head off, but it can poke him full of holes if you're fast enough.

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: I can be fast,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You'll have to work at it every day.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: How does it feel? Do you like the balance?

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: I think so,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: First lesson,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Stick them with the pointy end.

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: I know which end to use,

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: Septa Mordane will take it away from me.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Not if she doesn't know you have it,

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: Who will I practice with?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You'll find someone,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: King's Landing is a true city, a thousand times the size of Winterfell. Until you find a partner, watch how they fight in the yard. Run, and ride, make yourself strong. And whatever you do…

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: …don't… tell… Sansa!

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I will miss you, little sister.

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: I wish you were coming with us.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Different roads sometimes lead to the same castle. Who knows?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I better go. I'll spend my first year on the Wall emptying chamber pots if I keep Uncle Ben waiting any longer.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Put down the sword first,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I almost forgot,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: All the best swords have names.

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: Like Ice,

Speaker: Arya Stark
Dialogue: Does this have a name? Oh, tell me.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Can't you guess?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Your very favorite thing.

Speaker: Arya Stark;Jon Snow
Dialogue: Needle!

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: My fellow magisters have doubled the size of the city guard,

Speaker: Jorah Mormont
Dialogue: Best we get Princess Daenerys wedded quickly before they hand half the wealth of Pentos away to sellswords and bravos,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: He can have her tomorrow, if he likes,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: So long as he pays the price.

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: I have told you, all is settled. Trust me. The khal has promised you a crown, and you shall have it.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Yes, but when?

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: When the khal chooses,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: He will have the girl first, and after they are wed he must make his procession across the plains and present her to the dosh khaleen at Vaes Dothrak. After that, perhaps. If the omens favor war.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: I piss on Dothraki omens. The Usurper sits on my father's throne. How long must I wait?

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: You have waited most of your life, great king. What is another few months, another few years?

Speaker: Jorah Mormont
Dialogue: I counsel you to be patient, Your Grace. The Dothraki are true to their word, but they do things in their own time. A lesser man may beg a favor from the khal, but must never presume to berate him.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Guard your tongue, Mormont, or I'll have it out. I am no lesser man, I am the rightful Lord of the Seven Kingdoms. The dragon does not beg.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: You woke the dragon,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: You woke the dragon, you woke the dragon.

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: The Dothraki mate like the animals in their herds. There is no privacy in a khalasar, and they do not understand sin or shame as we do.

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: A Dothraki wedding without at least three deaths is deemed a dull affair,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: These are no common servants, sweet sister,

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Illyrio and I selected them personally for you. Irri will teach you riding, Jhiqui the Dothraki tongue, and Doreah will instruct you in the womanly arts of love.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: She's very good, Illyrio and I can both swear to that.

Speaker: Jorah Mormont
Dialogue: It is a small thing, my princess, but all a poor exile could afford,

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: What are they?

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Dragon's eggs, from the Shadow Lands beyond Asshai,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: The eons have turned them to stone, yet still they burn bright with beauty.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: I shall treasure them always.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: This is a gift worthy of a great warrior, O blood of my blood, and I am but a woman. Let my lord husband bear these in my stead.

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: A handsome gift, Khaleesi,

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: Most lucky.

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Silver for the silver of your hair, the khal says.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: She's beautiful,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: She is the pride of the khalasar,

Speaker: Illyrio Mopatis
Dialogue: Custom decrees that the khaleesi must ride a mount worthy of her place by the side of the khal.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: What should I do?

Speaker: Jorah Mormont
Dialogue: Take the reins and ride. You need not go far.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: Tell Khal Drogo that he has given me the wind.

Speaker: Viserys Targaryen
Dialogue: Please him, sweet sister, or I swear, you will see the dragon wake as it has never woken before.

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: I am the blood of the dragon,

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: I am the blood of the dragon. I am the blood of the dragon.

Speaker: Drogo
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: You speak the Common Tongue,

Speaker: Drogo
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Drogo
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: Is that the only word you know?

Speaker: Drogo
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Drogo
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Drogo
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Drogo
Dialogue: No?

Speaker: Daenerys Targaryen
Dialogue: Yes,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Up, Stark!

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Up, up! We have matters of state to discuss.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: By all means,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Come inside, Your Grace.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: No, no, no,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: The camp is full of ears. Besides, I want to ride out and taste this country of yours.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Gods,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: it feels good to get out and ride the way a man was meant to ride! I swear, Ned, this creeping along is enough to drive a man mad.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: That damnable wheelhouse, the way it creaks and groans, climbing every bump in the road as if it were a mountain… I promise you, if that wretched thing breaks another axle, I'm going to burn it, and Cersei can walk!

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I will gladly light the torch for you.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Good man!

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I've half a mind to leave them all behind and just keep going.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I do believe you mean it.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I do, I do,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: What do you say, Ned? Just you and me, two vagabond knights on the kingsroad, our swords at our sides and the gods know what in front of us, and maybe a farmer's daughter or a tavern wench to warm our beds tonight.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Would that we could,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: but we have duties now, my liege… to the realm, to our children, I to my lady wife and you to your queen. We are not the boys we were.
About Character: Robb Stark;Sansa Stark;Arya Stark;Bran Stark;Rickon Stark;Catelyn Stark;Cersei Lannister;Joffrey Baratheon;Myrcella Baratheon;Tommen Baratheon

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: You were never the boy you were,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: More's the pity. And yet there was that one time… what was her name, that common girl of yours? Becca? No, she was one of mine, gods love her, black hair and these sweet big eyes, you could drown in them. Yours was… Aleena? No. You told me once. Was it Merryl? You know the one I mean, your bastard's mother?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Her name was Wylla,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: and I would sooner not speak of her.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Wylla. Yes.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: She must have been a rare wench if she could make Lord Eddard Stark forget his honor, even for an hour. You never told me what she looked like…

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Nor will I. Leave it be, Robert, for the love you say you bear me. I dishonored myself and I dishonored Catelyn, in the sight of gods and men.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Gods have mercy, you scarcely knew Catelyn.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I had taken her to wife. She was carrying my child.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: You are too hard on yourself, Ned. You always were. Damn it, no woman wants Baelor the Blessed in her bed.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Well, I'll not press you if you feel so strong about it, though I swear, at times you're so prickly you ought to take the hedgehog as your sigil.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: The barrows of the First Men.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Have we ridden onto a graveyard?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: There are barrows everywhere in the north, Your Grace,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: This land is old.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: And cold,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Well, I did not bring you out here to talk of graves or bicker about your bastard. There was a rider in the night, from Lord Varys in King's Landing. Here.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: What is the source for this information?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Do you remember Ser Jorah Mormont?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Would that I might forget him,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Ser Jorah is now in Pentos, anxious to earn a royal pardon that would allow him to return from exile,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Lord Varys makes good use of him.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: So the slaver has become a spy,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I would rather he become a corpse.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Varys tells me that spies are more useful than corpses,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Jorah aside, what do you make of his report?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Daenerys Targaryen has wed some Dothraki horselord. What of it? Shall we send her a wedding gift?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: A knife, perhaps. A good sharp one, and a bold man to wield it.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I see no babes. Only dragonspawn.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Your Grace, the girl is scarcely more than a child. You are no Tywin Lannister, to slaughter innocents.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: And how long will this one remain an innocent?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: This child will soon enough spread her legs and start breeding more dragonspawn to plague me.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Nonetheless,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: the murder of children… it would be vile… unspeakable…

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Unspeakable?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: What Aerys did to your brother Brandon was unspeakable. The way your lord father died, that was unspeakable. And Rhaegar… how many times do you think he raped your sister? How many hundreds of times?
About Character: Aerys II Targaryen;Brandon Stark;Rickard Stark;Rhaegar Targaryen;Lyanna Stark

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I will kill every Targaryen I can get my hands on, until they are as dead as their dragons, and then I will piss on their graves.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You can't get your hands on this one, can you?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: No, gods be cursed. Some pox-ridden Pentoshi cheesemonger had her brother and her walled up on his estate with pointy-hatted eunuchs all around them, and now he's handed them over to the Dothraki. I should have had them both killed years ago, when it was easy to get at them, but Jon was as bad as you. More fool I, I listened to him.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Jon Arryn was a wise man and a good Hand.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: This Khal Drogo is said to have a hundred thousand men in his horde. What would Jon say to that?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: He would say that even a million Dothraki are no threat to the realm, so long as they remain on the other side of the narrow sea,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: The barbarians have no ships. They hate and fear the open sea.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Perhaps. There are ships to be had in the Free Cities, though. I tell you, Ned, I do not like this marriage. There are still those in the Seven Kingdoms who call me Usurper. Do you forget how many houses fought for Targaryen in the war? They bide their time for now, but give them half a chance, they will murder me in my bed, and my sons with me. If the beggar king crosses with a Dothraki horde at his back, the traitors will join him.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: He will not cross,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: And if by some mischance he does, we will throw him back into the sea. Once you choose a new Warden of the East—

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: For the last time, I will not name the Arryn boy Warden. I know the boy is your nephew, but with Targaryens climbing in bed with Dothraki, I would be mad to rest one quarter of the realm on the shoulders of a sickly child.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Yet we still must have a Warden of the East. If Robert Arryn will not do, name one of your brothers. Stannis proved himself at the siege of Storm's End, surely.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: That is,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: unless you have already promised the honor to another.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: What if I have?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: It's Jaime Lannister, is it not?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Yes,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Kingslayer,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: An able and courageous man, no doubt,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: but his father is Warden of the West, Robert. In time Ser Jaime will succeed to that honor. No one man should hold both East and West.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I will fight that battle when the enemy appears on the field,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: At the moment, Lord Tywin looms eternal as Casterly Rock, so I doubt that Jaime will be succeeding anytime soon. Don't vex me about this, Ned, the stone has been set.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Your Grace, may I speak frankly?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I seem unable to stop you,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Can you trust Jaime Lannister?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: He is my wife's twin, a Sworn Brother of the Kingsguard, his life and fortune and honor all bound to mine.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: As they were bound to Aerys Targaryen's,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Why should I mistrust him? He has done everything I have ever asked of him. His sword helped win the throne I sit on.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: He swore a vow to protect his king's life with his own. Then he opened that king's throat with a sword.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Seven hells, someone had to kill Aerys!

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: If Jaime hadn't done it, it would have been left for you or me.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: We were not Sworn Brothers of the Kingsguard,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Do you remember the Trident, Your Grace?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: I won my crown there. How should I forget it?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You took a wound from Rhaegar,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: So when the Targaryen host broke and ran, you gave the pursuit into my hands. The remnants of Rhaegar's army fled back to King's Landing. We followed. Aerys was in the Red Keep with several thousand loyalists. I expected to find the gates closed to us.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Instead you found that our men had already taken the city. What of it?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Not our men,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Lannister men. The lion of Lannister flew over the ramparts, not the crowned stag. And they had taken the city by treachery.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Treachery was a coin the Targaryens knew well,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Lannister paid them back in kind. It was no less than they deserved. I shall not trouble my sleep over it.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You were not there,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: There was no honor in that conquest.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: The Others take your honor!

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: What did any Targaryen ever know of honor? Go down into your crypt and ask Lyanna about the dragon's honor!

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You avenged Lyanna at the Trident,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: That did not bring her back.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: The gods be damned. It was a hollow victory they gave me. A crown… it was the girl I prayed them for. Your sister, safe… and mine again, as she was meant to be. I ask you, Ned, what good is it to wear a crown? The gods mock the prayers of kings and cowherds alike.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I cannot answer for the gods, Your Grace… only for what I found when I rode into the throne room that day,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Aerys was dead on the floor, drowned in his own blood. His dragon skulls stared down from the walls. Lannister's men were everywhere. Jaime wore the white cloak of the Kingsguard over his golden armor. I can see him still. Even his sword was gilded. He was seated on the Iron Throne, high above his knights, wearing a helm fashioned in the shape of a lion's head. How he glittered!

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: This is well known,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I was still mounted. I rode the length of the hall in silence, between the long rows of dragon skulls. It felt as though they were watching me, somehow. I stopped in front of the throne, looking up at him. His golden sword was across his legs, its edge red with a king's blood. My men were filling the room behind me. Lannister's men drew back. I never said a word. I looked at him seated there on the throne, and I waited. At last Jaime laughed and got up. He took off his helm, and he said to me, 'Have no fear, Stark. I was only keeping it warm for our friend Robert. It's not a very comfortable seat, I'm afraid.'

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: You think I should mistrust Lannister because he sat on my throne for a few moments?

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Jaime was all of seventeen, Ned. Scarce more than a boy.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Boy or man, he had no right to that throne.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Perhaps he was tired,

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Killing kings is weary work. Gods know, there's no place else to rest your ass in that damnable room. And he spoke truly, it is a monstrous uncomfortable chair. In more ways than one.

Speaker: Robert Baratheon
Dialogue: Well, now I know Jaime's dark sin, and the matter can be forgotten. I am heartily sick of secrets and squabbles and matters of state, Ned. It's all as tedious as counting coppers. Come, let's ride, you used to know how. I want to feel the wind in my hair again.

Speaker: Yoren
Dialogue: Rapers,

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: I warn you, Lannister, you'll find no inns at the Wall,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: No doubt you'll find some place to put me,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: As you might have noticed, I'm small.

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: You will not like the ride, I promise you that,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Why do you read so much?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Look at me and tell me what you see.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Is this some kind of trick? I see you. Tyrion Lannister.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: You are remarkably polite for a bastard, Snow. What you see is a dwarf. You are what, twelve?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Fourteen,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Fourteen, and you're taller than I will ever be. My legs are short and twisted, and I walk with difficulty. I require a special saddle to keep from falling off my horse. A saddle of my own design, you may be interested to know. It was either that or ride a pony. My arms are strong enough, but again, too short. I will never make a swordsman. Had I been born a peasant, they might have left me out to die, or sold me to some slaver's grotesquerie. Alas, I was born a Lannister of Casterly Rock, and the grotesqueries are all the poorer. Things are expected of me. My father was the Hand of the King for twenty years. My brother later killed that very same king, as it turns out, but life is full of these little ironies. My sister married the new king and my repulsive nephew will be king after him. I must do my part for the honor of my House, wouldn't you agree? Yet how? Well, my legs may be too small for my body, but my head is too large, although I prefer to think it is just large enough for my mind. I have a realistic grasp of my own strengths and weaknesses. My mind is my weapon. My brother has his sword, King Robert has his warhammer, and I have my mind… and a mind needs books as a sword needs a whetstone, if it is to keep its edge.
About Character: Tywin Lannister;Jaime Lannister;Robert Baratheon;Joffrey Baratheon;Cersei Lannister;Aerys II Targaryen

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: That's why I read so much, Jon Snow.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: What are you reading about?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Dragons,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: What good is that? There are no more dragons,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: So they say,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Sad, isn't it? When I was your age, used to dream of having a dragon of my own.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You did?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Oh, yes. Even a stunted, twisted, ugly little boy can look down over the world when he's seated on a dragon's back.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I used to start fires in the bowels of Casterly Rock and stare at the flames for hours, pretending they were dragonfire. Sometimes I'd imagine my father burning. At other times, my sister.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Don't look at me that way, bastard. I know your secret. You've dreamt the same kind of dreams.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I wouldn't…

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: No? Never?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Well, no doubt the Starks have been terribly good to you. I'm certain Lady Stark treats you as if you were one of her own. And your brother Robb, he's always been kind, and why not? He gets Winterfell and you get the Wall. And your father… he must have good reasons for packing you off to the Night's Watch…

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Stop it,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: The Night's Watch is a noble calling!

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: You're too smart to believe that. The Night's Watch is a midden heap for all the misfits of the realm. I've seen you looking at Yoren and his boys. Those are your new brothers, Jon Snow, how do you like them? Sullen peasants, debtors, poachers, rapers, thieves, and bastards like you all wind up on the Wall, watching for grumkins and snarks and all the other monsters your wet nurse warned you about. The good part is there are no grumkins or snarks, so it's scarcely dangerous work. The bad part is you freeze your balls off, but since you're not allowed to breed anyway, I don't suppose that matters.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Stop it!

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Help me,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Don't help me, then. I'll sit right here until you leave.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Ask me nicely.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I should be very grateful for your kind assistance, Jon,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Down, Ghost,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Why did he attack me?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Maybe he thought you were a grumkin.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Oh, gods,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I suppose I do rather look like a grumkin. What does he do to snarks?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You don't want to know.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Want some?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: It's true, isn't it?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: What you said about the Night's Watch.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: If that's what it is, that's what it is.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: That's good, bastard. Most men would rather deny a hard truth than face it.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Most men,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: But not you.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: not me. I seldom even dream of dragons anymore. There are no dragons.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Come, we had better return to camp before your uncle calls the banners.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: More pepper,

Speaker: Benjen Stark
Dialogue: There you are. Jon, damn it, don't go off like that by yourself. I thought the Others had gotten you.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: It was the grumkins,

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: It is past time that we reviewed the figures, my lady,

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: You'll want to know how much this royal visit cost us.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I have no need to look at figures, Maester Luwin,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I know what the visit cost us. Take the books away.

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: My lady, the king's party had healthy appetites. We must replenish our stores before—

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I said, take the books away. The steward will attend to our needs.

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: We have no steward,

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: Poole went south to establish Lord Eddard's household at King's Landing.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Oh, yes. I remember.

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: There are several appointments that require your immediate attention, my lady. Besides the steward, we need a captain of the guards to fill Jory's place, a new master of horse—

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: A master of horse?

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: Yes, my lady. Hullen rode south with Lord Eddard, so—

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: My son lies here broken and dying, Luwin, and you wish to discuss a new master of horse? Do you think I care what happens in the stables? Do you think it matters to me one whit? I would gladly butcher every horse in Winterfell with my own hands if it would open Bran's eyes, do you understand that? Do you?

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: Yes, my lady, but the appointments—

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: I'll make the appointments,

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: I have prepared a list of those we might wish to consider for the vacant offices,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Good men,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: We'll talk about them tomorrow.

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: Very good, my lord.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Leave us now,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Mother, what are you doing?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: What am I doing?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: How can you ask that? What do you imagine I'm doing? I am taking care of your brother. I am taking care of Bran.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Is that what you call it? You haven't left this room since Bran was hurt. You didn't even come to the gate when Father and the girls went south.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I said my farewells to them here, and watched them ride out from that window.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I can't leave him, even for a moment, not when any moment could be his last. I have to be with him, if… if…

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: He's not going to die, Mother. Maester Luwin says the time of greatest danger has passed.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: And what if Maester Luwin is wrong? What if Bran needs me and I'm not here?

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Rickon needs you,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: He's only three, he doesn't understand what's happening. He thinks everyone has deserted him, so he follows me around all day, clutching my leg and crying. I don't know what to do with him.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Mother, I need you too. I'm trying but I can't… I can't do it all by myself.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Bran's.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Don't,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Bran needs to stay warm.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: He needs to hear them sing,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Shaggydog and Grey Wind,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: You can tell them apart if you listen close.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Make them stop!

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I can't stand it, make them stop, make them stop, kill them all if you must, just make them stop!

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Don't be afraid, Mother. They would never hurt him.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Close your eyes,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Rest. Maester Luwin tells me you've hardly slept since Bran's fall.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I can't,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Gods forgive me, Robb, I can't, what if he dies while I'm asleep, what if he dies, what if he dies…

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Oh, gods, close the window!

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: If you swear to me you'll sleep.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Dogs,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: All the dogs are barking. They've never done that before…

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Fire,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Help me,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Help me with Bran.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: The library tower's on fire,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Thank the gods,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Mother, stay here. I'll come back as soon as the fire's out.

Speaker: Unknown
Dialogue: Fire!

Speaker: Unknown (Bran's assassin)
Dialogue: You weren't s'posed to be here,

Speaker: Unknown (Bran's assassin)
Dialogue: No one was s'posed to be here.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Unknown (Bran's assassin)
Dialogue: It's a mercy,

Speaker: Unknown (Bran's assassin)
Dialogue: He's dead already.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: No, you can't.

Speaker: Unknown (Bran's assassin)
Dialogue: You weren't s'posed to be here,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Thank you,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Bring me some bread and honey,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: and take word to Maester Luwin that my bandages want changing.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Who was he?

Speaker: Hallis Mollen
Dialogue: No one knows his name,

Speaker: Hallis Mollen
Dialogue: He was no man of Winterfell, m'lady, but some says they seen him here and about the castle these past few weeks.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: One of the king's men, then,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: or one of the Lannisters'. He could have waited behind when the others left.

Speaker: Hallis Mollen
Dialogue: Maybe,

Speaker: Hallis Mollen
Dialogue: With all these strangers filling up Winterfell of late, there's no way of saying who he belonged to.

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: He'd been hiding in your stables,

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: You could smell it on him.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: And how could he go unnoticed?

Speaker: Hallis Mollen
Dialogue: Between the horses Lord Eddard took south and them we sent north to the Night's Watch, the stalls were half-empty. It were no great trick to hide from the stableboys. Could be Hodor saw him, the talk is that boy's been acting queer, but simple as he is…

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: We found where he'd been sleeping,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: He had ninety silver stags in a leather bag buried beneath the straw.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: It's good to know my son's life was not sold cheaply,

Speaker: Hallis Mollen
Dialogue: Begging your grace, m'lady, you saying he was out to kill your boy?

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: That's madness.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: He came for Bran,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: He kept muttering how I wasn't supposed to be there. He set the library fire thinking I would rush to put it out, taking any guards with me. If I hadn't been half-mad with grief, it would have worked.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Why would anyone want to kill Bran?

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Gods, he's only a little boy, helpless, sleeping…

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: If you are to rule in the north, you must think these things through, Robb. Answer your own question. Why would anyone want to kill a sleeping child?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: How is my son, Maester?

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: Unchanged, my lady.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Do you have the answer yet?

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Someone is afraid Bran might wake up,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: afraid of what he might say or do, afraid of something he knows.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Very good.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: We must keep Bran safe. If there was one killer, there could be others.

Speaker: Hallis Mollen
Dialogue: How many guards do you want, rn'lady?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: So long as Lord Eddard is away, my son is the master of Winterfell,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Put one man in the sickroom, night and day, one outside the door, two at the bottom of the stairs. No one sees Bran without my warrant or my mother's.

Speaker: Hallis Mollen
Dialogue: As you say, m'lord.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Do it now,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: And let his wolf stay in the room with him,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Yes,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Yes.

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: Lady Stark,

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: did you chance to notice the dagger the killer used?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: The circumstances did not allow me to examine it closely, but I can vouch for its edge,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Why do you ask?

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: We found the knife still in the villain's grasp. It seemed to me that it was altogether too fine a weapon for such a man, so I looked at it long and hard. The blade is Valyrian steel, the hilt dragonbone. A weapon like that has no business being in the hands of such as him. Someone gave it to him.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Robb, close the door.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: What I am about to tell you must not leave this room,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I want your oaths on that. If even part of what I suspect is true, Ned and my girls have ridden into deadly danger, and a word in the wrong ears could mean their lives.

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: Lord Eddard is a second father to me,

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: I do so swear.

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: You have my oath,

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: And mine, my lady,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: And you, Robb?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: My sister Lysa believes the Lannisters murdered her husband, Lord Arryn, the Hand of the King,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: It comes to me that Jaime Lannister did not join the hunt the day Bran fell. He remained here in the castle.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I do not think Bran fell from that tower,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I think he was thrown.

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: My lady, that is a monstrous suggestion,

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: Even the Kingslayer would flinch at the murder of an innocent child.

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: Oh, would he?

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: I wonder.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: There is no limit to Lannister pride or Lannister ambition,

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: The boy had always been surehanded in the past,

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: He knew every stone in Winterfell.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: Gods,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: If this is true, he will pay for it.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: I'll kill him myself!

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: Put that away! The Lannisters are a hundred leagues away. Never draw your sword unless you mean to use it. How many times must I tell you, foolish boy?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I see my son is wearing steel now.

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: I thought it was time.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Past time,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Winterfell may have need of all its swords soon, and they had best not be made of wood.

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: My lady, if it comes to that, my House owes yours a great debt.

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: All we have is conjecture. This is the queen's beloved brother we mean to accuse. She will not take it kindly. We must have proof, or forever keep silent.

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: Your proof is in the dagger,

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: A fine blade like that will not have gone unnoticed.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Someone must go to King's Landing.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: I'll go,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Your place is here. There must always be a Stark in Winterfell.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I must go myself.

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: My lady,

Speaker: Luwin
Dialogue: is that wise? Surely the Lannisters would greet your arrival with suspicion.

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: What about Bran?

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: You can't mean to leave him.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I have done everything I can for Bran,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: His life is in the hands of the gods and Maester Luwin. As you reminded me yourself, Robb, I have other children to think of now.

Speaker: Theon Greyjoy
Dialogue: You will need a strong escort, my lady,

Speaker: Robb Stark
Dialogue: I'll send Hal with a squad of guardsmen,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: A large party attracts unwelcome attention. I would not have the Lannisters know I am coming.

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: My lady, let me accompany you at least. The kingsroad can be perilous for a woman alone.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I will not be taking the kingsroad,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Two riders can move as fast as one, and a good deal faster than a long column burdened by wagons and wheelhouses. I will welcome your company, Ser Rodrik. We will follow the White Knife down to the sea, and hire a ship at White Harbor. Strong horses and brisk winds should bring us to King's Landing well ahead of Ned and the Lannisters.

Dialogue: —a whore. I heard him. What of it?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Lord Eddard Stark was not a man to sleep with whores,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: His honor—

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: —did not prevent him from fathering a bastard. Did it?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Can I go?

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: You go when I tell you to go.

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: Look at me when I'm talking to you, boy.

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: Words won't make your mother a whore. She was what she was, and nothing Toad says can change that. You know, we have men on the Wall whose mothers were whores.

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: You think you had it hard, being a high lord's bastard?

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: That boy Jeren is a septon's get, and Cotter Pyke is the baseborn son of a tavern wench. Now he commands Eastwatch by the Sea.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I don't care,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I don't care about them and I don't care about you or Thorne or Benjen Stark or any of it. I hate it here. It's too… it's cold.

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: Yes. Cold and hard and mean, that's the Wall, and the men who walk it. Not like the stories your wet nurse told you. Well, piss on the stories and piss on your wet nurse. This is the way it is, and you're here for life, same as the rest of us.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Life,

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: Yes, life,

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: A long life or a short one, it's up to you, Snow. The road you're walking, one of your brothers will slit your throat for you one night.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: They're not my brothers,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: They hate me because I'm better than they are.

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: No. They hate you because you act like you're better than they are. They look at you and see a castle-bred bastard who thinks he's a lordling.

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: You're no lordling. Remember that. You're a Snow, not a Stark. You're a bastard and a bully.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: A bully?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: They were the ones who came after me. Four of them.

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: Four that you've humiliated in the yard. Four who are probably afraid of you. I've watched you fight. It's not training with you. Put a good edge on your sword, and they'd be dead meat; you know it, I know it, they know it. You leave them nothing. You shame them. Does that make you proud?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: They're all older than me,

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: Older and bigger and stronger, that's the truth. I'll wager your master-at-arms taught you how to fight bigger men at Winterfell, though. Who was he, some old knight?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Ser Rodrik Cassel,

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: Now think on this, boy. None of these others have ever had a master-at-arms until Ser Alliser. Their fathers were farmers and wagonmen and poachers, smiths and miners and oars on a trading galley. What they know of fighting they learned between decks, in the alleys of Oldtown and Lannisport, in wayside brothels and taverns on the kingsroad. They may have clacked a few sticks together before they came here, but I promise you, not one in twenty was ever rich enough to own a real sword.

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: So how do you like the taste of your victories now, Lord Snow?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Don't call me that!

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I never… I didn't think…

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: Best you start thinking,

Speaker: Donal Noye
Dialogue: That, or sleep with a dagger by your bed. Now go.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: And beyond a doubt the most useless,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Makes you wonder what lies beyond,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Lannister. I didn't see—I mean, I thought I was alone.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: There's much to be said for taking people unawares. You never know what you might learn.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: You won't learn anything from me,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Oh, I learn things everywhere I go.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: As I was saying… why is it that when one man builds a wall, the next man immediately needs to know what's on the other side?

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: You do want to know what's on the other side, don't you?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: It's nothing special,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: The rangers say it's just woods and mountains and frozen lakes, with lots of snow and ice.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: And the grumkins and the snarks,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Let us not forget them, Lord Snow, or else what's that big thing for?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Don't call me Lord Snow.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Would you rather be called the Imp? Let them see that their words can cut you, and you'll never be free of the mockery. If they want to give you a name, take it, make it your own. Then they can't hurt you with it anymore.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Come, walk with me. They'll be serving some vile stew in the common hall by now, and I could do with a bowl of something hot.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I don't see your wolf,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I chain him up in the old stables when we're training. They board all the horses in the east stables now, so no one bothers him. The rest of the time he stays with me. My sleeping cell is in Hardin's Tower.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: That's the one with the broken battlement, no? Shattered stone in the yard below, and a lean to it like our noble king Robert after a long night's drinking? I thought all those buildings had been abandoned.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: No one cares where you sleep. Most of the old keeps are empty, you can pick any cell you want.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I'll be sure to tell your father to arrest more stonemasons, before your tower collapses.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: It's better that I'm by myself,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: The rest of them are scared of Ghost.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Wise boys,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: The talk is, your uncle is too long away.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: He said he'd be back by my name day,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: They were looking for Ser Waymar Royce, his father is bannerman to Lord Arryn. Uncle Benjen said they might search as far as the Shadow Tower. That's all the way up in the mountains.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I hear that a good many rangers have vanished of late,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Perhaps the grumkins are hungry this year.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Barley, onion, carrot,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Someone should tell the cooks that turnip isn't a meat.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: It's mutton stew.

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: Snow.

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: The Lord Commander wants to see you. Now.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Is it my uncle?

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Is he returned safe?

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: The Lord Commander is not accustomed to waiting,

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: And I am not accustomed to having my commands questioned by bastards.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Stop it, Thorne. You're frightening the boy.

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: Keep out of matters that don't concern you, Lannister. You have no place here.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I have a place at court, though,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: A word in the right ear, and you'll die a sour old man before you get another boy to train. Now tell Snow why the Old Bear needs to see him. Is there news of his uncle?

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: No,

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: This is another matter entirely. A bird arrived this morning from Winterfell, with a message that concerns his brother.

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: His half brother.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Bran,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Something's happened to Bran.

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: Jon,

Speaker: Tyrion Lannister
Dialogue: I am truly sorry.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Bran,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: What does it say about Bran?

Speaker: Jeor Mormont
Dialogue: I am told you can read.

Speaker: Mormont's raven
Dialogue: Corn,

Speaker: Mormont's raven
Dialogue: Corn, corn.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: He woke up,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: The gods gave him back.

Speaker: Jeor Mormont
Dialogue: Crippled,

Speaker: Jeor Mormont
Dialogue: I'm sorry, boy. Read the rest of the letter.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: My brother is going to live,

Speaker: Mormont's raven
Dialogue: Live! Live!

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: My brother is going to live,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Bran is going to live!

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: Here, read it,

Speaker: Grenn
Dialogue: Stay away from me now, you bastard.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I'm sorry about your wrist. Robb used the same move on me once, only with a wooden blade. It hurt like seven hells, but yours must be worse. Look, if you want, I can show you how to defend that.

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: Lord Snow wants to take my place now.

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: I'd have an easier time teaching a wolf to juggle than you will training this aurochs.

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I'll take that wager, Ser Alliser,

Speaker: Jon Snow
Dialogue: I'd love to see Ghost juggle.

Speaker: Alliser Thorne
Dialogue: That was a grievous error, Lord Snow,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: It will be convenient on the morrow,

Speaker: Unknown (King's Steward)
Dialogue: I shall give the councillors your regrets, my lord.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: No, damn it,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I will see them. Pray give me a few moments to change into something more presentable.

Speaker: Unknown (King's Steward)
Dialogue: Yes, my lord,

Speaker: Unknown (King's Steward)
Dialogue: We have given you Lord Arryn's former chambers in the Tower of the Hand, if it please you. I shall have your things taken there.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: My thanks,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: It seems the council has urgent need of me. See that my daughters find their bedchambers, and tell Jory to keep them there. Arya is not to go exploring.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: My wagons are still straggling through the city. I shall need appropriate garments.

Speaker: Unknown (King's Steward)
Dialogue: It will be my great pleasure,

Speaker: Varys
Dialogue: Lord Stark, I was grievous sad to hear about your troubles on the kingsroad. We have all been visiting the sept to light candles for Prince Joffrey. I pray for his recovery.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Your gods have heard you,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: The prince grows stronger every day.

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: I see you have arrived safely, Lord Stark,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: And you as well,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You must forgive me, but sometimes you look the very image of your brother Robert.

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: A poor copy,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Though much better dressed,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Lord Renly spends more on clothing than half the ladies of the court.

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: There are worse crimes,

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: The way you dress, for one.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: I have hoped to meet you for some years, Lord Stark. No doubt Lady Catelyn has mentioned me to you.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: She has,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I understand you knew my brother Brandon as well.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Rather too well,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: I still carry a token of his esteem. Did Brandon speak of me too?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Often, and with some heat,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: I should have thought that heat ill suits you Starks,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Here in the south, they say you are all made of ice, and melt when you ride below the Neck.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I do not plan on melting soon, Lord Baelish. You may count on it.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Maester Pycelle, I trust you are well.

Speaker: Pycelle
Dialogue: Well enough for a man of my years, my lord,

Speaker: Pycelle
Dialogue: yet I do tire easily, I fear.

Speaker: Pycelle
Dialogue: Perhaps we might begin soon,

Speaker: Pycelle
Dialogue: I fear I shall fall asleep if we wait much longer.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: As you will.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: My lords,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I am sorry to have kept you waiting.

Speaker: Varys
Dialogue: You are the King's Hand,

Speaker: Varys
Dialogue: We serve at your pleasure, Lord Stark.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: We are but five,

Speaker: Varys
Dialogue: Lord Stannis took himself to Dragonstone not long after the king went north,

Speaker: Varys
Dialogue: and our gallant Ser Barristan no doubt rides beside the king as he makes his way through the city, as befits the Lord Commander of the Kingsguard.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Perhaps we had best wait for Ser Barristan and the king to join us,

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: If we wait for my brother to grace us with his royal presence, it could be a long sit.

Speaker: Varys
Dialogue: Our good King Robert has many cares,

Speaker: Varys
Dialogue: He entrusts some small matters to us, to lighten his load.

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: What Lord Varys means is that all this business of coin and crops and justice bores my royal brother to tears,

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: so it falls to us to govern the realm. He does send us a command from time to time.

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: This morning he commanded me to ride ahead with all haste and ask Grand Maester Pycelle to convene this council at once. He has an urgent task for us.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Gods be good,

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: What Lord Eddard means to say,

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: is that His Grace instructs us to stage a great tournament in honor of his appointment as the Hand of the King.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: How much?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Forty thousand golden dragons to the champion. Twenty thousand to the man who comes second, another twenty to the winner of the melee, and ten thousand to the victor of the archery competition.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Ninety thousand gold pieces,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: And we must not neglect the other costs. Robert will want a prodigious feast. That means cooks, carpenters, serving girls, singers, jugglers, fools…

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: Fools we have in plenty,

Speaker: Pycelle
Dialogue: Will the treasury bear the expense?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: What treasury is that?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Spare me the foolishness, Maester. You know as well as I that the treasury has been empty for years. I shall have to borrow the money. No doubt the Lannisters will be accommodating. We owe Lord Tywin some three million dragons at present, what matter another hundred thousand?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Are you claiming that the Crown is three million gold pieces in debt?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: The Crown is more than six million gold pieces in debt, Lord Stark. The Lannisters are the biggest part of it, but we have also borrowed from Lord Tyrell, the Iron Bank of Braavos, and several Tyroshi trading cartels. Of late I've had to turn to the Faith. The High Septon haggles worse than a Dornish fishmonger.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Aerys Targaryen left a treasury flowing with gold. How could you let this happen?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: The master of coin finds the money. The king and the Hand spend it.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I will not believe that Jon Arryn allowed Robert to beggar the realm,

Speaker: Pycelle
Dialogue: Lord Arryn was a prudent man, but I fear that His Grace does not always listen to wise counsel.

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: My royal brother loves tournaments and feasts,

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: and he loathes what he calls 'counting coppers.'

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I will speak with His Grace,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: This tourney is an extravagance the realm cannot afford.

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: Speak to him as you will,

Speaker: Renly Baratheon
Dialogue: we had still best make our plans.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Another day,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Forgive me, my lords,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: I am tired. Let us call a halt for today and resume when we are fresher.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: You're going the wrong way, Stark. Come with me.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: This is not the way to my chambers,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Did I say it was? I'm leading you to the dungeons to slit your throat and seal your corpse up behind a wall,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: We have no time for this, Stark. Your wife awaits.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: What game are you playing, Littlefinger? Catelyn is at Winterfell, hundreds of leagues from here.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Oh?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Then it appears someone has managed an astonishing impersonation. For the last time, come. Or don't come, and I'll keep her for myself.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: We're outside the castle,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: You are a hard man to fool, Stark,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Was it the sun that gave it away, or the sky? Follow me. There are niches cut in the rock. Try not to fall to your death, Catelyn would never understand.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: You are growing old and slow, Stark,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: No matter, we ride the rest of the way.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: A brothel,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You've brought me all this way to take me to a brothel.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Your wife is inside,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Brandon was too kind to you,

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: My lord, no,

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: He speaks the truth.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: This is no business of yours,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Ser Rodrik?

Speaker: Rodrik Cassel
Dialogue: Your lady awaits you upstairs.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Catelyn is truly here? This is not some strange jape of Littlefinger's?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Would that it were, Stark,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Follow me, and try to look a shade more lecherous and a shade less like the King's Hand. It would not do to have you recognized. Perhaps you could fondle a breast or two, just in passing.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: My lady,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Oh, very good,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: You recognized her.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I feared you'd never come, my lord,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Petyr has been bringing me reports. He told me of your troubles with Arya and the young prince. How are my girls?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Both in mourning, and full of anger,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Cat, I do not understand. What are you doing in King's Landing? What's happened?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Is it Bran? Is he…

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: It is Bran, but not as you think,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Then how? Why are you here, my love? What is this place?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Just what it appears,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: A brothel. Can you think of a less likely place to find a Catelyn Tully?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: As it chances, I own this particular establishment, so arrangements were easily made. I am most anxious to keep the Lannisters from learning that Cat is here in King's Landing.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Why?

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You've been hurt.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Gods. Those are deep cuts… a gash from a sword or… how did this happen, my lady?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: This blade was sent to open Bran's throat and spill his life's blood.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: But… who… why would…

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Let me tell it all, my love. It will go faster that way. Listen.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: The Imp's dagger,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Why should Tyrion Lannister want Bran dead? The boy has never done him harm.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Do you Starks have nought but snow between your ears?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: The Imp would never have acted alone.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: If the queen had a role in this or, gods forbid, the king himself… no, I will not believe that.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Most likely the king did not know,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: It would not be the first time. Our good Robert is practiced at closing his eyes to things he would rather not see.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: The accusation is treason either way. Accuse the king and you will dance with Ilyn Payne before the words are out of your mouth. The queen… if you can find proof, and if you can make Robert listen, then perhaps…

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: We have proof,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: We have the dagger.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: This?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: A sweet piece of steel, but it cuts two ways, my lord. The Imp will no doubt swear the blade was lost or stolen while he was at Winterfell, and with his hireling dead, who is there to give him the lie?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: My counsel is to drop that in the river and forget that it was ever forged.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Lord Baelish, I am a Stark of Winterfell. My son lies crippled, perhaps dying. He would be dead, and Catelyn with him, but for a wolf pup we found in the snow. If you truly believe I could forget that, you are as big a fool now as when you took up sword against my brother.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: A fool I may be, Stark… yet I'm still here, while your brother has been moldering in his frozen grave for some fourteen years now. If you are so eager to molder beside him, far be it from me to dissuade you, but I would rather not be included in the party, thank you very much.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You would be the last man I would willingly include in any party, Lord Baelish.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: You wound me deeply.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: For my part, I always found you Starks a tiresome lot, but Cat seems to have become attached to you, for reasons I cannot comprehend. I shall try to keep you alive for her sake. A fool's task, admittedly, but I could never refuse your wife anything.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I told Petyr our suspicions about Jon Arryn's death,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: He has promised to help you find the truth.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Very well,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You spoke of Varys. Does the eunuch know all of it?

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Not from my lips,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: You did not wed a fool, Eddard Stark. But Varys has ways of learning things that no man could know. He has some dark art, Ned, I swear it.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: He has spies, that is well known,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: It is more than that,

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: Ser Rodrik spoke to Ser Aron Santagar in all secrecy, yet somehow the Spider knew of their conversation. I fear that man.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Leave Lord Varys to me, sweet lady. If you will permit me a small obscenity—and where better for it—I hold the man's balls in the palm of my hand.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Or would, if he were a man, or had any balls. You see, if the pie is opened, the birds begin to sing, and Varys would not like that. Were I you, I would worry more about the Lannisters and less about the eunuch.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: My lady,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: there is nothing more you can do here. I want you to return to Winterfell at once. If there was one assassin, there could be others. Whoever ordered Bran's death will learn soon enough that the boy still lives.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I had hoped to see the girls…

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: That would be most unwise,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: The Red Keep is full of curious eyes, and children talk.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: He speaks truly, my love,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Take Ser Rodrik and ride for Winterfell. I will watch over the girls. Go home to our sons and keep them safe.
About Character: Rodrik Cassel;Arya Stark;Sansa Stark;Bran Stark;Rickon Stark;Robb Stark

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: As you say, my lord.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Would the lord and lady like the use of a bedchamber?

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: I should warn you, Stark, we usually charge for that sort of thing around here.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: A moment alone, that's all I ask,

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Very well.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Don't be too long. It is past time the Hand and I returned to the castle, before our absence is noted.

Speaker: Catelyn Stark
Dialogue: I will not forget the help you gave me, Petyr. When your men came for me, I did not know whether they were taking me to a friend or an enemy. I have found you more than a friend. I have found a brother I'd thought lost.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: I am desperately sentimental, sweet lady. Best not tell anyone. I have spent years convincing the court that I am wicked and cruel, and I should hate to see all that hard work go for naught.

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: You have my thanks as well, Lord Baelish.

Speaker: Petyr Baelish
Dialogue: Oh, now there's a treasure,

Speaker: Eddard Stark
Dialogue: Once you are home, send word to Helman Tallhart and Galbart Glover under my seal. They are to raise a hundred bowmen each and fortify Moat Cailin. Two hundred determined archers can hold the Neck against an army. Instruct Lord Manderly that he is to strengthen and repair all his defenses at White Harbor, and see that they are well manned. And from this day on, I want a careful watch kept over Theon Greyjoy. If there is war, we shall have sore need of his father's fleet.
About Character: Helman Tallhart;Galbart Glover;Wyman Manderly;Theon Greyjoy;Balon Greyjoy
